success.question_text: What two solids make up the feed bin?

stimulus_1.text: The diagram shows a feed bin on a farm.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Prisms have two identical faces and the other faces are rectangles. Pyramids have a base, after which the pyramid is named, and triangular faces that meet at a point.

success.question_text: Which of these is the front view of Carson’s solid?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When a solid is built from a number of cubes it can be viewed from a number of directions. These views from different directions may not be the same. Sometimes cubes cannot be seen because they are blocked by others.

success.question_text: How many different acute angles can be seen in this diagram?
How many cubes will only have one face painted?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

If a solid is formed using small cubes it may need to be dismantled to solve a problem.

success.question_text: Which could be the net of this box?

review_5.column_1_text:
Tip

Practise drawing, cutting out and folding nets.

review_4.column_1_text:
The direction in which the plane is travelling is South-West.

Tip

Draw a diagram to help understand and solve the problem.

success.question_text: In which of the solids is the cross-section a triangle?

stimulus_1.text: A cross-section is a slice of a prism, parallel to the base.

review_3.column_1_text:
The cuts are shown on each of the solids.

This means that the cross-sections on both solids are triangles.

Tip

A cross-section is the slice formed when a solid is cut. The faces that are the ends of a prism are parallel and congruent polygons, e.g. a rectangular prism has ends that are identical and parallel rectangles. Each end of a prism is called a base.

choice_4.label: Neither Solid A nor Solid B

success.question_text: What did his paper look like when he unfolded it?

stimulus_1.text: Oliver folded a piece of paper in half and then folded it in half again by folding the top down as shown in the diagram.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When paper folding, the number of layers of paper gives the number of repeated cut-out shapes.

success.question_text: What is the view from the left side?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When a solid is built from a number of identical cubes it can be viewed from a number of directions. These views from different directions may not be the same. Sometimes cubes cannot be seen because they are blocked by others.

success.question_text: Which of these designs does not have half-turn symmetry?

stimulus_1.text: A design has half-turn symmetry if it looks the same when turned (about its centre) through half a turn or 180 degrees.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

If a design has half-turn symmetry it looks the same when turned upside down. To easily see whether a design has half-turn symmetry, turn the page upside down.

success.question_text: How many squares are in the figure?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When asked to identify squares on a diagram, make sure squares of all sizes are found.

success.question_text: What is the shortest distance from Allenton to Clareville?

stimulus_1.text: The diagram shows a map of the towns in the local area and the distances along the roads between them.

review_1.column_1_text:
Solution

The shortest route from Allenton to Clareville passes through Finlay and Edgewater.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

If a map is not drawn to scale then you cannot judge distances just by looking at them.

stimulus_1.text: The diagram shows a map of the towns in the local area and the distances along the roads between them.

stimulus_3.text: Toby travels from Clareville through Edgewater to Finlay. Jordan travels from Clareville through Birdwood and Allenton to Finlay. Jordan travels at twice the speed of Toby.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

If you travel at twice the speed you will travel twice the distance in the same time.

choice_3.label: They should both arrive at the same time.

choice_4.label: There is not enough information to determine who will arrive first.

stimulus_1.text: The diagram shows a map of the towns in the local area and the distances along the roads between them.

stimulus_3.text: Piret intends to ride her bike from Birdwood to Finlay, stopping at Darcy for 15 minutes and at Edgewater for half an hour. If she rides at 10 kilometres per hour, how long will it take Piret to travel from Birdwood to Finlay?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Remember it is not always necessary to work out the exact answer. You only need to determine which of the options will work. For example, in this question you didn’t need to know exactly how long the journey took.

success.question_text: What type of solid did Natasha draw?

stimulus_1.text: Natasha drew a solid that had four triangular faces and one rectangular face.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

A pyramid is a solid with a polygon as the shape of its base and with all other faces triangular. These triangular faces meet at a vertex. A pyramid is named according to the shape of its base.

A prism is a solid with identical polygons as its two bases and rectangles as the other faces.

success.question_text: What is the sum of the lengths of all the edges of the cube?

stimulus_1.text: A cube has sides of length 3 cm.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

A solid can be described by its number of faces, edges and vertices.

success.question_text: How many cubes of any size are in the solid?

stimulus_1.text: The solid is a rectangular prism made from small cubes.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When a solid is made from small cubes many will be hidden from view. Remember to count all cubes, visible or hidden.

success.question_text: Through how many degrees will the plane turn?

stimulus_2.text:
An air force plane is flying in a south-easterly direction.

The pilot is instructed to change direction and fly in a southerly direction.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

A compass rose shows directions to North, East, South and West. In between these directions are North-East, South-East, South-West and North-West.

stimulus_1.text: The numbers on the opposite faces of this cube add to 7.

stimulus_3.text: The cube is rolled to the left (over the bottom left side edge), and then rolled over the new bottom front edge twice.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Practise rolling a die to see what happens to the different faces.
